%N A300072 Decimal expansion of the positive member -y of a triple (x, y, z) solving a certain historical system of three equations.
%C A300072 The system of three equations is
%C A300072   x + y + z = 10,
%C A300072   x*z = y^2,
%C A300072   x^2 + y^2 = z^2.
%C A300072 See A300070 for the Havil reference and links to Abū Kāmil, who considered this system. This real solution was not given in Havil's book.
%C A300072 This solution is x = x2 := 10*A248750, -y = -y2 = present entry, z = z2 = A300073.
%C A300072 The other real solution with positive y is x = 10*A248752, y = A300070, z = A300071.
%C A300072 Note that X2 = x2/5, -Y2 = -y2/5 and Z2 = z2/5 solve the system of equations (i) X2 + Y2 + Z2 = 2, (ii) X2*Z2 = (Y2)^2 and (iii) (X2)^2 + (Y2)^2 = (Z2)^2.
%F A300072 -y2 = 5*(1 - phi - sqrt(phi)), with the golden section phi = (1 + sqrt(5))/2 = A001622.
%F A300072 The minimal polynomial is x^4 + 10*x^3 - 50*x^2 - 1000*x - 2500. - _Joerg Arndt_, Jul 21 2025
